definitions: feeling unable to express emotions or behave naturally due to self-consciousness or fear
having a process or reaction slowed down or prevented by a chemical substance
examples: She felt too inhibited to dance at the party
The inhibited teenager struggled to make new friends
The drug inhibited the growth of cancer cells
Certain medications have inhibited enzyme activity

definitions: not welcoming or friendly to guests, showing little warmth or generosity
having harsh conditions that make survival or habitation extremely difficult
examples: The innkeeper's inhospitable attitude drove customers away
Their inhospitable reception made us leave early
The inhospitable desert terrain challenged even experienced hikers
Mars has an inhospitable atmosphere for human life

definitions: showing no compassion or mercy, extremely cruel or brutal in behavior
exceeding normal human abilities or endurance in strength, speed, or capacity
examples: The inhuman treatment of prisoners violated international law
His inhuman cruelty shocked even hardened soldiers
She worked at an inhuman pace to finish
The athlete displayed inhuman strength during the competition

definitions: showing no compassion or kindness towards others, especially those who are suffering
examples: The inhumane conditions in the factory were exposed
Keeping animals in such small cages is inhumane

definitions: showing hostility or opposition, tending to obstruct or cause harm to something
examples: The new policies were inimical to small businesses
His inimical attitude made cooperation impossible

definitions: so unique or excellent that it cannot be imitated or matched by others
examples: Her inimitable style made her paintings instantly recognizable
The chef's inimitable sauce recipe remained a secret

definitions: able to be administered into the body using a needle and syringe
examples: The doctor prescribed an injectable form of insulin
Injectable vaccines provide faster immune response than pills

definitions: having physical damage or harm to the body from an accident or attack
feeling emotional pain from being insulted, wronged, or treated unfairly
examples: The injured player was carried off the field
Several injured passengers were taken to the hospital
She gave him an injured look after the comment
His injured pride made him refuse their help

definitions: causing or likely to cause damage, harm, or injury to someone or something
examples: Smoking has injurious effects on your health
The injurious remarks damaged their professional relationship

definitions: having pieces of material set into a surface to form a decorative pattern
examples: The inlaid marble floor displayed intricate patterns
She admired the inlaid mother-of-pearl on the box

definitions: situated in or towards the interior of a country, away from the sea
examples: They moved to an inland town for cheaper housing
The inland regions experience more extreme temperature variations

definitions: existing from birth rather than acquired, belonging to the essential nature of something
examples: Her innate musical talent emerged at age three
Humans have an innate capacity for language learning

definitions: located farthest within or at the deepest part of something physical
most private, secret, or closely guarded in thoughts or feelings
examples: The innermost chamber of the pyramid remained sealed
They reached the innermost part of the cave
She shared her innermost fears with her therapist
His diary revealed his innermost thoughts and desires

definitions: not harmful or offensive, unlikely to cause any damage or give offense
examples: The innocuous comment was misinterpreted as an insult
What seemed like innocuous symptoms became serious later

definitions: too many to be counted, existing in numbers so great as to be uncountable
examples: The night sky contains innumerable stars
She had received innumerable applications for the position

definitions: not objectionable or harmful, unlikely to upset or annoy anyone
examples: He chose inoffensive topics for dinner conversation
The movie's inoffensive humor appealed to all ages

definitions: unable to be treated or removed by surgical operation due to medical reasons
not able to function or be used, broken beyond practical repair
examples: The tumor was inoperable due to its location
The patient's inoperable condition required alternative treatment
The old machinery had become completely inoperable
Heavy damage left the vehicle inoperable

definitions: not working or functioning, having ceased to be in effect or operation
examples: The emergency exits were inoperative during the inspection
Several clauses in the contract had become inoperative

definitions: unusually or unreasonably large, going beyond what is normal or acceptable
examples: He spent an inordinate amount of time checking emails
The project required inordinate amounts of resources

definitions: composed of matter that is not derived from living organisms, relating to compounds without carbon
not arising from natural growth, artificially added or developed without proper integration
examples: Salt is an inorganic compound found in seawater
The soil contained high levels of inorganic minerals
The company's inorganic growth through acquisitions caused problems
The plot's inorganic subplot felt forced and unnatural

definitions: showing curiosity or a desire to learn, characterized by asking questions
examples: The student's inquiring mind impressed her teachers
He gave her an inquiring look, waiting for explanation

definitions: having or showing great curiosity, eager to learn or know more about things
examples: The inquisitive child asked endless questions about everything
Her inquisitive nature made her an excellent researcher

definitions: impossible to satisfy or fulfill, always wanting more of something
examples: He had an insatiable appetite for adventure novels
The media showed insatiable interest in the scandal

definitions: having words or symbols written, carved, or engraved on a surface
examples: The inscribed monument honored fallen soldiers
She treasured the inscribed watch from her grandfather

definitions: lacking confidence in oneself, anxious about one's adequacy or acceptance by others
not firmly fixed or attached, liable to give way or be lost
examples: The insecure teenager worried constantly about fitting in
His insecure behavior stemmed from childhood experiences
The insecure ladder wobbled with each step
Their insecure financial situation caused constant stress

definitions: showing lack of concern for others' feelings, thoughtless or tactless in behavior
not responsive or susceptible to physical stimuli or chemical agents
examples: His insensitive comments hurt her deeply
The insensitive manager ignored employee concerns
The damaged nerves were insensitive to touch
This film is insensitive to light exposure

definitions: unable to be separated or treated separately, always found or seen together
examples: The twins were inseparable throughout their childhood
Good management and communication are inseparable in business

definitions: situated or operating close to or moving towards the shore
examples: The inshore fishing boats returned before sunset
Inshore waters are generally calmer than open ocean

definitions: proceeding gradually with harmful effects, developing so slowly as to be unnoticed
examples: The disease had an insidious onset over months
Propaganda can have insidious effects on public opinion

definitions: having or showing an accurate and deep understanding of someone or something
examples: Her insightful analysis revealed hidden market trends
The therapist made several insightful observations about behavior

definitions: too small or unimportant to be worth consideration, having little or no meaning
examples: The difference in price was insignificant
He felt insignificant in the large corporation

definitions: not expressing genuine feelings, pretending to feel something that one does not
examples: His insincere apology fooled no one
She could detect the insincere flattery immediately

definitions: hinting at something bad in an indirect and unpleasant way
examples: His insinuating remarks about her past upset everyone
She didn't appreciate the insinuating tone of the question

definitions: lacking flavor or taste, weak or watery in substance
lacking vigor or interest, dull and boring in character or quality
examples: The hospital food was insipid and unappetizing
The insipid soup needed salt and spices
The movie's insipid plot put audiences to sleep
Their insipid conversation made the dinner party drag

definitions: demanding something forcefully and refusing to accept refusal or delay
examples: Her insistent knocking finally woke the neighbors
He was insistent that everyone follow safety protocols

definitions: showing a rude and arrogant lack of respect towards others
examples: The insolent student was sent to the principal
His insolent behavior cost him the promotion

definitions: unable to be dissolved in a liquid, especially water
impossible to solve or explain, having no solution
examples: Oil is insoluble in water
The mineral formed insoluble crystals
They faced an insoluble dilemma with no good options
The mystery remained insoluble despite years of investigation

definitions: unable to pay debts owed, having liabilities that exceed assets
examples: The insolvent company filed for bankruptcy protection
Many businesses became insolvent during the economic crisis

definitions: experiencing or relating to the chronic inability to fall asleep or stay asleep
examples: The insomniac patient tried various sleep medications
Her insomniac tendencies worsened during stressful periods

definitions: providing motivation or encouragement to do or feel something positive
examples: The coach's inspirational speech energized the team
She found the survivor's story deeply inspirational

definitions: showing brilliant creative thought or skill, exceptionally good or original
filled with motivation or creative impulse, influenced by divine or supernatural guidance
examples: The architect's inspired design won international awards
It was an inspired choice to cast her in the role
The inspired artist worked through the night
She felt inspired after attending the conference

definitions: filling someone with the urge or ability to do or feel something creative or worthwhile
examples: The teacher's inspiring dedication motivated her students
The mountain views were truly inspiring to behold

definitions: occurring or done instantly, without any delay between cause and effect
examples: The reaction was almost instantaneous
Modern communication allows instantaneous global connection

definitions: based on natural impulse rather than conscious thought, arising from innate tendency
examples: Her instinctive reaction saved the child from falling
Animals show instinctive fear of their natural predators

definitions: serving to instruct or enlighten, providing knowledge or information in a helpful way
examples: The documentary was both entertaining and instructive
His mistakes proved instructive for future projects

definitions: serving as a crucial means of achieving something, having an important role
relating to or performed on musical instruments rather than voices
examples: She was instrumental in negotiating the peace treaty
His support proved instrumental to the project's success
The band released an instrumental version of their hit
He preferred instrumental jazz to vocal performances

definitions: not enough in quantity, strength, or quality to meet a need or requirement
examples: The evidence was insufficient to convict him
Their savings proved insufficient for the emergency

definitions: relating to or characteristic of an island, isolated from outside influences
having a limited or narrow outlook, unwilling to consider different ideas
examples: The insular community maintained unique traditions
Their insular location protected them from invasion
His insular views prevented him from understanding others
The company's insular culture resisted change

definitions: showing disrespect or scorn, intended to offend someone's dignity
examples: His insulting remarks about her work were uncalled for
They found the low salary offer insulting

definitions: protected by insurance against possible loss, damage, illness, or death
examples: The insured property was protected against flood damage
All insured patients received full coverage for treatment
